The paper deals with complexity measures and communication complexity, which are central topics in theoretical computer science. The use of R\'enyi mutual information and information-theoretic techniques suggests that cs.IT (Information Theory) is a likely category. The focus on communication complexity and partition complexity suggests cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as likely categories. The use of probability distributions and factorization properties suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as a possible category. Finally, the use of information complexity measures and lower bounds suggests cs.LG (Machine Learning) as a possible category.
